[[File:Insula Csepel 2.png|thumb|200px|Satellite picture of Csepel Island. Note its mainly urban northern part and the other suburbs of [[Budapest]] along with its centre on the [[Danube]] to the north]]
'''Csepel Island''' (Hungarian: ''Csepel-sziget'') {{IPAc-en|'|tʃ|ei|p|əl}} is the largest island on the [[Danube River]] in [[Hungary]]. It is [[1 E4 m|48 km]] long; its width after 3&ndash;km sections of [[river bifurcation|bifurcation]] and rejoining ([[confluence]]) is 6–8 km. Its area comprises [[1 E8 m²|257 km²]] and its population is 165,000.<ref>[https://www.researchgate.net/publication/11837760_Speciation_of_beryllium_nickel_and_vanadium_in_soil_samples_from_Csepel_Island_Hungary_Fresenius_Journal_of_Analytical_Chemistry_370_768-775 Speciation of beryllium, nickel, and vanadium in soil samples from Csepel Island, Hungary. Fresenius Journal of Analytical Chemistry, 370, 768-775]</ref>
The isle extends south from [[Budapest]]; its northern point or section is [[Csepel]] &ndash; Budapest's District XXI. Most of the island is accessible from Budapest by [[HÉV|the suburban railway]]. Notable towns include [[Ráckeve]], [[Szigetszentmiklós]], [[Szigethalom]] and [[Tököl]]. Csepel island was the first centre of the [[Hungarian conquest of the Carpathian Basin]] ({{lang-hu|honfoglalás}}: "conquest of the homeland"), being the early homestead of [[Árpád]]'s tribe. The island is named after Árpád's [[Groom (horses)|horse groom]], Csepel.
It features Hungary's tallest structure, [[Lakihegy Tower]], a {{convert|314|m}} radio mast used today intermittently for power network control purposes.<ref>[http://www.baaa-acro.com/1929/archives/crash-of-a-fokker-f3-in-hungary-2-killed/ Crash of a Fokker F3 in Csepel Island: 2 killed]</ref><ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=cLY1z-XLd_IC&pg=PA109&lpg=PA109&dq=csepel+island&source=bl&ots=51aK3rDRn8&sig=VMLuOSnf9jB8JEgdXxc4NyFkICA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwji9MOI8fXKAhUiJJoKHao0B9w4HhDoAQhEMAY#v=onepage&q=csepel%20island&f=false The Battle for Budapest]</ref>
