[[Category:Names of places in Norway|Trondheim, Names of]]
[[Category:Etymologies of geographic names|Trondheim, Names of]]

{{Infobox surname | name = Navarro | image = | caption = | meaning = someone from [[Navarre]] | region = [[Spain]] | languageorigin= [[Spanish language|Spanish]] | nolinklanguage=yes | search = Navarro | variant = [[Navarra]] }}
'''Navarro''' is a surname of [[Spanish Language|Spanish]], [[Italian Language|Italian]], and [[Sephardi]] origin.<ref>https://www.ancestry.com/name-origin?surname=navarro</ref> Navarro is a [[habitational surname]] denoting someone from [[Navarre]] (Basque: ''Nafarroa'')<ref>http://www.ancestry.com/facts/navarro-name-meaning.ashx</ref> after the [[Kingdom of Navarre|Kingdom of Pamplona]] took on the new naming in the high Middle Ages, while also keeping its original meaning of '[[Basque language|Basque]]-speaking person' in a broader sense, an ethnic surname.<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Sainz Pezonaga | first1 = Jabier | author1-link = | title = Antroponimia Medieval Euskérica en la Navarra Tudelana | journal = Fontes Linguae Vasconum: Studia et Documenta | volume = 1 | issue = 93 | page = 340 | publisher = Gobierno de Navarra; Institución Príncipe de Viana | location = | date = May–August 2003 | url = http://dialnet.unirioja.es/servlet/articulo?codigo=664035 | issn =0343-6993}}</ref> Ultimately the name is derived from the Basque word ''naba'' (meaning 'plain next to mountains').<ref>{{cite book | editor = Hanks, Patrick | title = Dictionary of American Family Names | year = 2003 | publisher = Oxford University Press | isbn = 9780195081374 | doi = 10.1093/acref/9780195081374.001.0001}}</ref>
Found in [[Bologna]] (Bononia) in [[Emilia-Romagna|Emilia]] where it is the capital of the province of Bologna in Italy.{{Citation needed|date=October 2010}}
